Introduction¶

1) Problématique¶

Commenons par effectuer une segmentation de type RFM. Dans un premier temps nous allons restreindre le dataset aux variables RFM, puis nous effectuerons une classification de la clientle sur des critres de marketing classiques.

# Traitement des outliers
for i in [0, 2]:

    outlier_indices = []
    col = rfm.columns[i]
    percentile_5 = np.percentile(rfm[col], 5)
    percentile_95 = np.percentile(rfm[col], 95)
    outlier_indices.append(rfm[(rfm[col] < percentile_5) | (rfm[col] > percentile_95)].index)

rfm.drop(outlier_indices[0][:], inplace= True)
rfm.reset_index(inplace= True, drop= True)

2) Méthode des quantiles¶

In [7]:
#Mthode des quantiles
rfm['r_quartile'] = pd.qcut(rfm['recence'], 4,['4','3','2','1'])
rfm['f_quartile'] = 0
rfm.loc[rfm['frequence'] <= 1, 'f_quartile'] = 1
rfm.loc[(rfm['frequence'] > 1) & (rfm['frequence'] <= 2), 'f_quartile'] = 2
rfm.loc[(rfm['frequence'] > 2) & (rfm['frequence'] <= 3), 'f_quartile'] = 3
rfm.loc[(rfm['frequence'] > 3), 'f_quartile'] = 4

rfm['m_quartile'] = pd.qcut(rfm['montant'], 4,['1','2','3','4'])
rfm['RFM_Score'] = 100*rfm['r_quartile'].astype(int)+ 10*rfm['f_quartile'].astype(int) + rfm['m_quartile'].astype(int)
rfm

3) Segmentation des clients¶

In [10]:
def customer_segmentation(rfm_score):
  
  if rfm_score == 444:
    return 'VIP'
  
  elif  rfm_score >= 433 and rfm_score < 444:
    return 'Client trs rgulier'
  
  elif   rfm_score >=421 and rfm_score< 433:
    return 'Potentiel client rgulier '
  
  elif rfm_score>=344 and rfm_score < 421:
    return 'Nouveau client'
  
  elif rfm_score>=323 and rfm_score<344:
    return 'Client potentiel'
  
  elif rfm_score>=224 and rfm_score<323:
    return 'Risque de dsabonnement' 
  
  else:
    return 'Clients perdus'       
  
rfm['customer_segmentation'] = rfm['RFM_Score'].apply(customer_segmentation)

In [20]:
def r_score(x):
    if x <= quintiles['recence'][.2]:
        return 5
    elif x <= quintiles['recence'][.4]:
        return 4
    elif x <= quintiles['recence'][.6]:
        return 3
    elif x <= quintiles['recence'][.8]:
        return 2
    else:
        return 1

def fm_score(x, c):
    if x <= quintiles[c][.2]:
        return 1
    elif x <= quintiles[c][.4]:
        return 2
    elif x <= quintiles[c][.6]:
        return 3
    elif x <= quintiles[c][.8]:
        return 4
    else:
        return 5
In [21]:
rfm['R'] = rfm['recence'].apply(lambda x: r_score(x))
rfm['F'] = rfm['frequence'].apply(lambda x: fm_score(x, 'frequence'))
rfm['M'] = rfm['montant'].apply(lambda x: fm_score(x, 'montant'))

In [23]:
segt_map = {
    '[1-2][1-2]': 'hibernating',
    '[1-2][3-4]': 'at risk',
    '[1-2]5': 'can\'t loose',
    '3[1-2]': 'about to sleep',
    '33': 'need attention',
    '[3-4][4-5]': 'loyal customers',
    '41': 'promising',
    '51': 'new customers',
    '[4-5][2-3]': 'potential loyalists',
    '5[4-5]': 'champions'}

rfm['Segment'] = rfm['R'].map(str) + rfm['F'].map(str)
rfm['Segment'] = rfm['Segment'].replace(segt_map, regex=True)
rfm.head()

Conclusion¶

La segmentation RFM basique nous donne des clusters bien dfinis. Essayons d'aller plus loin avec un kMean et DBscan
